  <section class="section-pad">
    <div class="container m-prose" style="max-width:780px">
      <h2>What should our department check before deploying voice dictation across a team?</h2>
      <p>Three questions worth working through with your IT, information governance, and procurement leads before deploying Speech Recognition Cloud across a government team: what data leaves the workstation, what is stored anywhere, and how dictation fits the department's existing arrangements for handling official information.</p>
      <ol class="m-numbered">
        <li><strong>What does the software process, and where does the audio go?</strong><br/>Speech Recognition Cloud sends audio to the cloud for transcription. Audio is processed in memory only and immediately erased — never written to disk on our servers, never retained, and never accessible to our staff. Transcribed text is delivered to the cursor on the officer's own computer; we do not retain a copy. Custom vocabulary stays on the device. Our <a href="/privacy" class="m-link">privacy and data-handling statement</a> documents this in full and is the document to provide to your IT or information governance lead.</li>
        <li><strong>What data is stored anywhere on our infrastructure?</strong><br/>Only the officer's email address, and it is encrypted. We do not store audio, transcripts, custom vocabulary, voice profiles, or dictation history. There is no departmental content of any kind on our servers because there is nothing for us to store. The data path is: microphone to our service, transcription in memory, words to the cursor, audio erased.</li>
        <li><strong>How does dictation fit existing information-handling arrangements?</strong><br/>Government information has classification and handling rules set by the agency under the relevant Commonwealth and state frameworks. Each agency makes its own determination about whether and how a particular tool fits those frameworks, through its IT security, information governance, and procurement processes. The fact that no departmental content is stored on our infrastructure simplifies that determination, but it does not substitute for the department's own assessment. Practical workflow point: dictation in open-plan offices about content that is sensitive to overhear (HR matters, individual case files, security-relevant policy) raises the same considerations as a phone call about the same content in the same space — directional microphones, USB headsets, or the mobile app held close to the mouth all help with workflow hygiene.</li>
      </ol>
      <p>The information-handling frameworks that govern government dictation vary by jurisdiction. The three most relevant for our visitors are covered below. Each agency should make its own determination through its IT security, information governance, and procurement processes.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

